MP-EdgeCaseAddonsSpec

Resilience Patches for Coherence Systems
(Slow Harm, Authority Redundancy, and Catastrophic Continuity)

Author: Jason Beau Risch (Sati Dhamma)
Date: 2026
Version: 0.5 (Add-on / Patch Layer)
Status: Optional but Recommended
Scope: Cross-Spec (AuthorityInvocation, Stabilization, Reset, Rights)


---

Reader Orientation — What This Document Is (and Is Not)

This document is a patch layer: a collection of edge-case add-ons that harden the core specs against real-world deployment failure modes.

It is not a replacement for the Core Axiom, Bill of Functional Rights, AuthorityInvocationSpec, ResetSpec, or StabilizationSpec.
It exists to capture “what breaks first” and encode structural fixes without rewriting older files.

If these add-ons increase stability without coercion, keep them. If not, discard them.


---

Abstract

This add-on spec defines four resilience patches:

1. Dysregulation Intervention Pathway (slow harm / coercive dyads)


2. Authority as Redundant Slot (pool selection + fallback chain)


3. No-Step-Up as System Telemetry (failure treated as load signal, not moral defect)


4. Bridge Collapse Clause (catastrophic decapitation continuity)



These patches preserve the invariant:

> Coherence precedes authority.
Care is unconditional.
Authority returns to zero.
Pause and dissolution remain non-optional.




---

Patch A — Dysregulation Intervention Pathway

(Pre-Rupture Containment Without “Pre-Crime”)

A1. Purpose

Some harm is not “kinetic” at a single instant. It accumulates as slow violence:

coercive control

chronic intimidation

deprivation within a dyad

escalating fear/anger loops

chronic dysregulation leading to rupture


This patch adds an early-response pathway that activates on dysregulation convergence, not ideology, not prediction, and not moral suspicion.

A2. Activation Threshold (Non-Coercive)

Dysregulation intervention may activate when two or more independent channels converge, such as:

local social visibility within a Dunbar-scale cell

direct request for help (self-report)

repeated stress indicators (fear / anger / withdrawal patterns)

witnessed intimidation / control behavior

safety signals from multiple neighbors


This pathway does not activate stabilization/force roles.

It activates care-side co-regulation, check-ins, and support escalation.

A3. Intervention Ladder (Care-Side)

1. Neighbor Check-In (low-friction, non-accusatory)


2. Co-Regulation Support (presence, accompaniment, de-escalation)


3. Voluntary Separation / Safe Space Offer (sleep elsewhere, respite, cooling-off)


4. Support Escalation (trained mediators, clinicians, resource stabilization)


5. Mandatory Safe Pause Gate (only if kinetic harm becomes present or imminent)



A4. Constraint

> Dysregulation intervention may never remove care, dignity, shelter, or belonging.
It may only increase support and reduce load.



If kinetic harm becomes present, the StabilizationSpec threshold applies.


