Patch C — No-Step-Up as System Telemetry

(Refusal and Absence Treated as Load Signal)

C1. Purpose

In real emergencies, “nobody steps up” may occur due to:

depletion / burnout

mass shock

insufficient training

unresolved trauma load

inadequate requisites and care coverage


This must be treated as system telemetry, not moral failure.

C2. Rule

If invocation fails repeatedly:

the system logs a capacity collapse event

triggers automatic review of:

care sufficiency

training adequacy

staffing redundancy

role load and burnout patterns

environmental stressors



C3. Correction Loop (Non-Punitive)

After a capacity collapse event, the system must:

increase rest and reset availability

reduce role load

expand training coverage

widen redundancy pools

adjust requisites allocation


No punishment is permitted for refusal.

Refusal remains data.


---

Patch D — Bridge Collapse Clause

(Catastrophic Decapitation Continuity)

D1. Purpose

Catastrophic events can destroy the normal chain:

mass casualty events

communications failure

“all senior operators unavailable” scenarios


A coherent system must degrade gracefully rather than freeze.

D2. Activation Conditions (Extreme Only)

The Bridge Collapse Clause activates only if all are true:

kinetic harm is active or collapse is imminent

Tier III pool is unavailable

council is unavailable

inaction guarantees catastrophic loss


D3. Temporary Continuity Authority

In Bridge Collapse mode:

the nearest capable participant may assume minimal containment authority

scope limited to:

evacuation calls

shutdown of failing infrastructure

immediate harm interruption

“stop the bleeding” actions only



D4. Dissolution and Review

authority dissolves immediately when a normal decider/council becomes available

all actions are reviewed for system learning, not blame

no prestige or permanent authority accrues


This clause exists to prevent “freeze and die” failure.


